  "prompt": "Why does your head hurt after you cry?",
  "response": "Headaches after crying can be attributed to several factors:\n\n1. **Physical Tension**: Emotional distress during crying often leads to muscle tension, especially in the neck, shoulders, and head, which can result in tension headaches.\n\n2. **Dehydration**: Crying can cause fluid loss, which might lead to mild dehydration. Dehydration is a common trigger for headaches.\n\n3. **Sinus Pressure**: Crying can cause nasal congestion and sinus pressure, which can lead to a feeling of fullness or pain in the head.\n\n4. **Hormonal Changes**: Emotional stress can trigger the release of certain hormones like cortisol, which might contribute to headaches.\n\n5. **Fatigue**: Crying often occurs during times of emotional stress, which can lead to fatigue and subsequently, headaches.\n\n6. **Blood Pressure Changes**: The emotional and physical aspects of crying can temporarily alter your blood pressure, which might contribute to headaches.\n\nIf headaches after crying are severe or frequent, it might be a good idea to consult with a healthcare professional to rule out underlying causes or to discuss strategies for stress management.",
